{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:35:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16571"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16571"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.83,0,0,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9262"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75957"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9262"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61458"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"5387"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21942"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21945"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75957"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive tremor and stiffness affecting his right hand. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He has a resting tremor of the right hand, cogwheel rigidity at the right wrist, and bradykinesia with finger tapping. His gait shows reduced arm swing on the right side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would be most appropriate to use as a diagnostic challenge test for Parkinson\u0027s disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pramipexole","Levodopa","Selegiline","Amantadine","Anticholinergic medication"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cardinal features of parkinsonism, and a levodopa challenge test can help confirm the diagnosis of Parkinson\u0027s disease. \u003Cstrong\u003ELevodopa\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate medication for this purpose as a significant improvement in motor symptoms following administration strongly supports the diagnosis of Parkinson\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPramipexole\u003C/strong\u003E, a dopamine agonist, while effective in treating Parkinson\u0027s disease, is not typically used for diagnostic challenge testing as its response is less predictable and reliable than levodopa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelegiline\u003C/strong\u003E, a monoamine oxidase B inhibitor, works by increasing dopamine availability but has a slower onset of action and is not suitable for acute challenge testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmantadine\u003C/strong\u003E has multiple mechanisms of action and provides only modest symptomatic benefit. It is not reliable enough to be used as a diagnostic test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnticholinergic medication\u003C/strong\u003E may help tremor but does not provide improvement in motor symptoms needed for diagnostic confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe acute dopaminergic challenge test typically involves administering a dose of levodopa (levodopa/carbidopa) and assessing response using a standardise scale. A positive response supports the diagnosis of Parkinson\u0027s disease and suggests the patient will respond well to long-term levodopa therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Levodopa challenge testing can help confirm the diagnosis of Parkinson\u0027s disease and predict long-term response to therapy.","A positive response to levodopa (15-30% improvement in motor symptoms) supports the diagnosis of Parkinson\u0027s disease.","The levodopa challenge test should be performed in the morning with the patient in the \u0027off\u0027 state."],"references":["Schade S, Sixel-D\u00f6ring F, Ebentheuer J, Schulz X, Trenkwalder C, Mollenhauer B. Acute Levodopa Challenge Test in Patients with de novo Parkinson\u0027s Disease: Data from the DeNoPa Cohort. Mov Disord Clin Pract. 2017 Jun 30;4(5):755-762. doi: 10.1002/mdc3.12511. PMID: 30363372; PMCID: PMC6174366.","Saranza G, Lang AE. Levodopa challenge test: indications, protocol, and guide. J Neurol. 2021 Sep;268(9):3135-3143. doi: 10.1007/s00415-020-09810-7. Epub 2020 Apr 24. PMID: 32333167.","Kobylecki C. Update on the diagnosis and management of Parkinson\u0027s disease. Clin Med (Lond). 2020 Jul;20(4):393-398. doi: 10.7861/clinmed.2020-0220. PMID: 32675145; PMCID: PMC7385761"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61458"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16571"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61458"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T17:27:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T17:27:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9262"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75957"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"s